# Environment variables for the go aggregator web app (Next.js 15, App Router).
#
# Copy to `.env.local` for local development. In Next.js only variables prefixed
# with NEXT_PUBLIC_ are inlined into the browser bundle; every other variable is
# available only to server-side code (the API route handlers under app/api/* and
# the request-time middleware). Never commit real secrets — `.env.local` is
# git-ignored.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Client (browser) — NEXT_PUBLIC_*
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# URL prefix the app is served under. The app is deployed at the domain root on
# Vercel (and in local `next dev`), so leave this BLANK. It only exists so
# withBase() (src/basePath.ts) can prefix manual fetch()s for the bundled data
# files (graph.json, search-index.json, docs/*.json) if the app is ever mounted
# under a sub-path.
NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_PATH=

# NOTE: there is no client-side API URL variable. The search + package-graph API
# is served by Next route handlers (/api/graphql, /api/search, /api/health) on
# the SAME host as the app, so the frontend always calls it same-origin.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Server (API route handlers + middleware) — Elasticsearch
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Symbol search is Elasticsearch-backed when ELASTICSEARCH_URL is set, and falls
# back to an in-memory BM25 ranker when it is not (so search always works, even
# with no cluster). /api/health reports which backend is live.
#
# Local dev: bring up the bundled single-node cluster and point the app at it —
#   docker compose up -d
#   ELASTICSEARCH_URL=http://localhost:9200 pnpm dev
# The `symbols` index is created and bulk-loaded automatically on the first
# search (see api/_lib/es.ts).
#
# Production: set these in the Vercel project environment (Project Settings ->
# Environment Variables), NOT in a committed file. ELASTICSEARCH_API_KEY is sent
# as `Authorization: ApiKey <key>` and is only needed for secured clusters
# (e.g. Elastic Cloud).
#
# ELASTICSEARCH_URL=http://localhost:9200
# ELASTICSEARCH_API_KEY=<base64-encoded-api-key>
